column5: we generate large numbers of images, but they are not well annotated until they are processed and assembled for presentation.  The images that become sufficiently annotated for someone not in the group to interpret are typically the ones we publish.  we could ask the group to share pre-prints of manuscripts as an alternative
column29: easily transferrable and useful for some groups to compare with existing datasets

column5: Well-annotated data are useful for developing new machine learning models to automate the identification image features. Sharing un-annotated data (with subsequent manual annotation) is better than no data.
column29: It should not be required, but it is very helpful for model development studies to share these data (e.g. for cell lines) so that users of these cell lines in the future can confirm identity

column5: Level 2 seems appropriate for this data (i.e. adjustments referring to realignment or cropping to highlight main ROI, having images from all samples tested is important)
column9: To make this data reusable, level 1 data with proper gating information is required. If gating information is not included, then level 3 will be appropriate
column21: Plate reader output with properly labeled wells (i.e. labeling controls) is required for making this data reusable.
column25: Level 1 blot scans with labeled wells is required to make this data reusable. While I have not re-analyzed this kind of data, I can imagine that these data can be useful for generating models/algorithms for automatic band/intensity detection (for the interested person), or even fraud detection (western blots are highly manipulatable, I know of at least two papers that were retracted due to fraud blots)
column33: Even though it seems unintuitive, in my experience I have seen people analyze the raw data for qPCR in different ways with various assumptions. To make the data reusable, raw data from technical triplicates should be included.

column5: Recommend sending data for all cases and perhaps a representative image
column13: I don't work with clinical data so I'm not qualified to comment further
column25: A table of results should be sufficient, perhaps with a sample WB to show the specificity of the signal
column37: Table of results and representative image showing how measurements were made should be sufficient

column25: We use a WES capillary protein analysis system instead of traditional western blot.  This system is easier to anlyze and share raw data with.
